<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
  <meta charset="UTF-8" />
  <title>Security, CAPTCHA, HTTPS and Privacy Consent Report</title>
  <style>
    body {
      font-family: Calibri, Arial, sans-serif;
      font-size: 12pt;
      line-height: 1.4;
      color: #111;
      margin: 0.7in;
    }
    h1, h2, h3 {
      margin: 0 0 10px;
      color: #0f172a;
    }
    p { margin: 0 0 8px; }
    .meta p { margin: 0 0 4px; }
    .section { margin-top: 14px; }
    .caption {
      margin-top: 8px;
      font-size: 10.5pt;
      color: #334155;
    }
    img {
      width: 100%;
      max-width: 980px;
      border: 1px solid #cbd5e1;
    }
    .page-break {
      page-break-before: always;
      break-before: page;
      height: 0;
      margin: 0;
      border: 0;
    }
    ul, ol { margin: 0 0 10px 18px; }
  </style>
</head>
<body>
  <h1>Implementation Report: HTTPS, CAPTCHA and Privacy Consent Flow</h1>
  <div class="meta">
    <p><strong>Project:</strong> CodeNexa Academy</p>
    <p><strong>Prepared By:</strong> Development Team</p>
    <p><strong>Date:</strong> 07 April 2026</p>
  </div>

  <div class="section">
    <h2>Aim</h2>
    <p>To implement a secure website access and consent process where a visitor must pass CAPTCHA verification before interacting with the page, and then provide explicit privacy consent through Accept/Reject actions.</p>
  </div>

  <div class="section">
    <h2>Software Required</h2>
    <ul>
      <li>Visual Studio Code</li>
      <li>Modern browser (Chrome/Firefox/Edge)</li>
      <li>Python 3 (for local web server)</li>
      <li>.NET SDK tool: <em>dotnet dev-certs</em> (local HTTPS certificate)</li>
      <li>Node.js (for HTTPS proxy when required)</li>
    </ul>
  </div>

  <div class="section">
    <h2>Theory</h2>
    <p>Web security combines transport security, bot protection, and user consent management:</p>
    <ol>
      <li><strong>HTTPS:</strong> Protects data in transit using TLS encryption.</li>
      <li><strong>CAPTCHA:</strong> Blocks automated bot actions by requiring human verification.</li>
      <li><strong>Privacy Consent:</strong> Provides user-controlled choice to accept or reject consent-related storage behavior.</li>
    </ol>
    <p>In this implementation, CAPTCHA is shown before page usage, and Accept/Reject appears only after successful CAPTCHA, matching production-style security flow.</p>
  </div>

  <div class="section">
    <h2>Procedure</h2>
    <ol>
      <li>Configured HTTPS for localhost using trusted development certificate.</li>
      <li>Added pre-load CAPTCHA gate that blocks interaction until successful verification.</li>
      <li>Implemented refreshable CAPTCHA challenge and new challenge generation on failure.</li>
      <li>Removed case-sensitivity issues by switching to numeric CAPTCHA code.</li>
      <li>Displayed privacy consent controls only after CAPTCHA verification.</li>
      <li>Captured evidence screenshots for each state: wrong input, refresh, correct solve, accept, and reject.</li>
    </ol>
  </div>

  <img src="report_screenshots/01_https_gate.png" alt="HTTPS page with CAPTCHA gate" />
  <p class="caption"><strong>Figure 1:</strong> HTTPS page loaded with pre-load CAPTCHA gate.</p>

  <div class="page-break"></div>
  <h2>Evidence 2: Wrong CAPTCHA Attempt</h2>
  <img src="report_screenshots/02_captcha_wrong.png" alt="Wrong CAPTCHA attempt" />
  <p class="caption"><strong>Figure 2:</strong> Incorrect CAPTCHA input blocks progression and displays failure state.</p>

  <div class="page-break"></div>
  <h2>Evidence 3: CAPTCHA Refresh</h2>
  <img src="report_screenshots/03_captcha_refresh.png" alt="CAPTCHA refresh button" />
  <p class="caption"><strong>Figure 3:</strong> Refresh button generates a new CAPTCHA challenge for retry.</p>

  <div class="page-break"></div>
  <h2>Evidence 4: Correct CAPTCHA and Page Unlock</h2>
  <img src="report_screenshots/04_captcha_correct_unlocked.png" alt="Correct CAPTCHA solved" />
  <p class="caption"><strong>Figure 4:</strong> Correct CAPTCHA allows page access and continues to consent stage.</p>

  <div class="page-break"></div>
  <h2>Evidence 5: Accept/Reject Visible After Verification</h2>
  <img src="report_screenshots/05_consent_accept_reject_visible.png" alt="Consent options visible" />
  <p class="caption"><strong>Figure 5:</strong> Privacy consent options are shown only after CAPTCHA verification.</p>

  <div class="page-break"></div>
  <h2>Evidence 6: Consent Accepted</h2>
  <img src="report_screenshots/06_after_accept.png" alt="After accept action" />
  <p class="caption"><strong>Figure 6:</strong> Accept action processed successfully.</p>

  <div class="page-break"></div>
  <h2>Evidence 7: Consent Rejected</h2>
  <img src="report_screenshots/07_after_reject.png" alt="After reject action" />
  <p class="caption"><strong>Figure 7:</strong> Reject action processed successfully.</p>

  <div class="section">
    <h2>Conclusion</h2>
    <p>The website now follows a stricter and clearer security sequence: HTTPS transport, pre-load CAPTCHA verification, and privacy consent decision. The flow prevents automatic/bot access before interaction and ensures consent appears only after human verification. All required states (wrong CAPTCHA, refreshed challenge, correct CAPTCHA, accept, and reject) were validated and documented.</p>
  </div>
</body>
</html>
